ngland":"英国英格兰","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"英国越可爾多卡斯特","lifeSummary":"Maude Mann是Mann的女儿，于大约1510年出生在英国越可爾多卡斯特。她和William Brewster至少有2个儿子。她去世于1558年10月11日之后在英国越可爾，埋葬在英国英格兰。"},"hr":{"about 1510–after 11 October 1558":"oko 1510.–nakon 11. listopada 1558.","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1520–Male":"1520–preminuo","–1559":"–1559","–Female":"preminula","1505–Male":"1505–preminuo","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1490–Male":"1490–preminuo","after 11 October 1558":"nakon 11. listopada 1558.","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","about 1537":"oko 1537.","1520":"1520","about 1535":"oko 1535.","about 1510":"oko 1510.","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"Engleska, United Kingdom","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"cs":{"about 1510–after 11 October 1558":"okolo 1510–po 11. října 1558","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1520–Male":"1520–Zesnulý","–1559":"–1559","–Female":"Zesnulá","1505–Male":"1505–Zesnulý","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1490–Male":"1490–Zesnulý","after 11 October 1558":"po 11. října 1558","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","about 1537":"okolo 1537","1520":"1520","about 1535":"okolo 1535","about 1510":"okolo 1510","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1510–after 11 October 1558":"omkring 1510–efter 11. oktober 1558","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1520–Male":"1520–Afdød","–1559":"–1559","–Female":"Afdød","1505–Male":"1505–Afdød","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1490–Male":"1490–Afdød","after 11 October 1558":"efter 11. oktober 1558","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","about 1537":"omkring 1537","1520":"1520","about 1535":"omkring 1535","about 1510":"omkring 1510","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1510–after 11 October 1558":"circa 1510–na 11 oktober 1558","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1520–Male":"1520–Overleden","–1559":"–1559","–Female":"Overleden","1505–Male":"1505–Overleden","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1490–Male":"1490–Overleden","after 11 October 1558":"na 11 oktober 1558","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","about 1537":"circa 1537","1520":"1520","about 1535":"circa 1535","about 1510":"circa 1510","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1510–after 11 October 1558":"about 1510–after 11 October 1558","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1520–Male":"1520–Deceased","–1559":"–1559","–Female":"Deceased","1505–Male":"1505–Deceased","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1490–Male":"1490–Deceased","after 11 October 1558":"after 11 October 1558","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","about 1537":"about 1537","1520":"1520","about 1535":"about 1535","about 1510":"about 1510","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mann","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a fierce or strong man, or for a man contrasted with a boy, from Middle English, Middle High German <i>man</i>, German <i>Mann</i> ‘man’. In some cases it may have arisen as an occupational name for a servant, from the medieval use of the term to describe a person of inferior social status. The Jewish surname can be artificial.","English and German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Manno</i>, found in Old English as <i>Mann</i> or <i>Manna</i>. This originated either as a byname or else as a short form of a compound name containing the element <i>man</i> ‘man’, such as   Hermann  .","English: habitational name from the Isle of Man."],"variants":[{"name":"Manon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Marcos, Adolfo, Alejandro, Ana, Ana Maria, Angel, Bienvenido, Cristobal, Eduardo, Ernesto, Fernando.","Galician (<b>Mañón</b>): variant of <b>Maañón</b>, a habitational name from Mañón (formerly <i>Maañón</i>), a place in Galicia (Spain). The surname <i>Mañón</i> is not found in Galicia (Spain).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Manno</i> (see   Mann   2), with the Old French oblique case ending."]},{"name":"Mannel","meanings":["German (<b>Männel</b>): from a pet form of   Mann   2.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the French places called Mesnil, from Old French <i>mesnil</i> (from Latin <i>mansionile</i>, a diminutive of <i>mansio</i> ‘abode, habitation’), used of the country domain where a noble lived with his family and retainers. As a surname it may also be used of a member of the household, retainer.","English: from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Maginhild</i>, itself from <i>magin-</i> ‘power’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Manns","meanings":["German: patronymic from   Mann   1 and 2.","English: variant of   Mann   1, 2 and 5, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Mansell","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands):","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Old French <i>mansel</i> ‘inhabitant of Le Mans or the surrounding area of Maine’. The place was originally named in Latin <i>(ad) Ceromannos</i>, from the name of the Gaulish tribe living there, the <i>Ceromanni</i>. The name was shortened to <i>Celmans</i> and then became <i>Le Mans</i> as a result of the mistaken identification of the first syllable with the Old French demonstrative adjective.","status name for a particular type of feudal tenant, Anglo-Norman French <i>mansel</i>, one who occupied a <i>manse</i> (from Late Latin <i>mansa</i> ‘dwelling’), a measure of land sufficient to support one family."]},{"name":"Mankin","meanings":["English: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Man(n)</i> (see   Mann   2), or a nickname from a diminutive of the noun<i>man</i>, with the sense of ‘little man’."]},{"name":"Hermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Jurgen, Mathias, Gottlieb, Horst, Juergen, Klaus, Lorenz, Bernd, Dieter, Erwin.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Harman   5.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German name (see 1 above). Compare   Herman  ."]},{"name":"Man","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wai, Chan, Cheuk, Kin, Kwok, Sai, Shek, Tong, Chi, Choong, Chung Yee, Hin.","Flemish and Dutch (also <b>De Man</b>): from Middle Dutch <i>man</i> ‘man, husband, vassal’ (compare   Mann  ).","English: variant of   Mann  ."]},{"name":"Mannes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Aase, Erik, Lars.  German Klaus, Kurt.","German: patronymic from   Mann  .","Dutch: from the personal name <i>Mannes</i>, a short form of <i>Hermannus</i> (see   Hermann  )."]},{"name":"Mon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jorge, Jose, Armando, Dulce, Eduardo, Emilio, Enedina, Francisca, Gregorio, Guillermina, Jose Luis, Josefa.  Chinese Chin, Hon, Hyeon, Jin, Kam Shing, Khin, Kin, Maung, Mei, Seng, Sing, Zhi Ming.","Asturian-Leonese: habitational name from Mon in Asturias (Spain).","Catalan: from a short form of the Marian name <i>Mare de Déu del Món</i> ‘Mother of God of the World’."]},{"name":"Manheim","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avraham, Moshe, Surie, Zalman.","Jewish (Ashkenazic) and German: habitational name from the city of Mannheim in southwestern Germany (formerly the residence of the electors Palatine), so named from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Manno</i> (see   Mann   2) + Old High German <i>heim</i> ‘homestead’. Mannheim was not fortified or chartered until the beginning of the 17th century, until which time it was just a small fishing village. This surname is rare in Germany. Compare   Mannheim  ."]}]},{"name":"Maude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Maud  , the usual spelling of the name in North America."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maude Mann was born about 1510, in Doncaster, Y